- Texas. 11 Aug 2017. 1 Jan 2016-31 July 2017, 219 pregnant women with laboratory evidence of possible recent Zika virus infection were identified in Texas, including 49 (22 percent) with laboratory-confirmed Zika virus). One woman was infected in Texas; all others were exposed outside the United States and its territories. Zika virus testing was completed for 80 (43 percent) of the 185 infants or fetuses, and Zika virus-associated birth defects were documented in 15 (8 percent) pregnancies (14 live-born infants and one fetal loss), including 6 (17 percent) of the 36 infants or fetal losses delivered by women with laboratory-confirmed Zika virus infection. Of these, 10 infants or fetuses had microcephaly; 5 of those with microcephaly had additional birth defects, including holoprosencephaly [the brain doesn't properly divide into the right and left hemispheres], hydranencephaly [brain's cerebral hemispheres replaced by sacs filled with cerebrospinal fluid], craniosynostosis [premature fusion of one or more cranial sutures, often resulting in an abnormal head shape], and clubfeet [feet turned inward]. Zika virus-associated birth defects identified in the remaining 3 infants included holoprosencephaly, cataracts, and ventral pons hypoplasia.
https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/volumes/66/wr/mm6631a5.htm?s_cid=mm6631a5_e

[Neurological effects not only occur in fetuses and neonates, there are occasional cases in adults as well. A report describes a case of ZIKV meningoencephalitis and probable myelitis and its associated magnetic resonance imaging findings that rapidly resolved during recovery in a previously healthy adult. (http://www.ajtmh.org/content/journals/10.4269/ajtmh.16-0921). - Mod. TY]

